[[File:Kakinomoto Miya Mandala (Yamato Bunkakan).jpg|thumb|150px|(Reference image) Kakinomoto-no-miya Mandala (Yamato Bunkakan collection)]]
'''Wanishita Shrine''' (わにしたじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Ichinomoto-cho|Q17174137|WD=Q17174137|1=Ichinomoto}}, {{ill|lt=Tenri|Q502196|WD=Q502196|1=Tenri, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha small shrine|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, formerly a {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, and a {{ill|lt=shinsen-heihaku-ryo kyoshinsha|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History|p=72}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}} - enshrined in the center{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History|p=329}}.
* {{ill|WD=Q276944|lt=Okuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Onamuchi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}} - enshrined on the left{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History|p=329}}.
* {{ill|WD=Q505469|lt=Kushinadahime|Q505469|WD=Q505469|WD=Q505469|lt=Kushinadahime-no-Mikoto|1=Kushinadahime}} - enshrined on the right{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History|p=329}}.

=== History ===
The shrine stands where the old Tatsuta Road and {{ill|lt=Kami-kaido (Kami-tsu-michi)|Q11360095|WD=Q11360095|lt=Kami-tsu-michi|1=Kami Kaidō}} intersect{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History|p=329}}{{sfn|Great Dictionary of Temples and Shrines|p=832}}. In contrast to {{ill|lt=Wanishita Shrine (Yamatokoriyama)|Q59282593|WD=Q59282593|lt=Wanishita Shrine|1=Wanishita Shrine (Q59282593)}} (Shimoharumichi-no-miya), about 2.5 {{ill|lt=kilometers|Q828224|WD=Q828224|1=Kilometre}} west in {{ill|lt=Yamatokoriyama|Q118213|WD=Q118213|1=Yamatokōriyama}}, it is also called Kamiharumichi-no-miya or Kamiharumichi Tenno{{sfn|Great Dictionary of Temples and Shrines|p=832}}. It is considered one of the "two seats of Wanishita Shrine" listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} for Soekami District{{sfn|Great Dictionary of Temples and Shrines|p=832}}. Originally, this shrine appears to have enshrined the ancestral deity of the Kakinomoto clan, relatives of the {{ill|lt=Wani clan|Q11417873|WD=Q11417873|1=Wani clan}}, and that original deity may have been the Wani ancestor {{ill|lt=Ama-tarashihiko-kunioshi-hito-no-Mikoto|Q11443593|WD=Q11443593|1=Prince Ametarashihiko}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History|p=329}}.

The shrine site was in Ichii-no-sho, an estate of {{ill|lt=Todai-ji|Q460367|WD=Q460367|1=Tōdai-ji}}. ''{{ill|lt=Todai-ji Zoku Yoroku|Q11526471|WD=Q11526471|1=Tōdaiji Zoku Yōroku}}'' records that from the Jingo-keiun era, irrigation ponds and waterways were developed and Yokota Road (Tatsuta Road) was repaired{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History|p=329}}{{sfn|Great Dictionary of Temples and Shrines|p=832}}. ''{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kakinomoto Ason Hitomaro Kanmon|1=UNKNOWN}}'' says, "Beside Isonokami Temple in Soekami District there is a shrine called Harumichi-sha, and within it a temple called Kakinomoto-dera," indicating the old use of the name Harumichi and the existence of Kakinomoto-dera as the shrine-temple{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History|p=329}}{{sfn|Great Dictionary of Temples and Shrines|p=832}}. Nara-period roof tiles were excavated from Hitomaru-zuka in the former precincts of Kakinomoto-dera{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History|p=329}}{{sfn|Great Dictionary of Temples and Shrines|p=832}}.

In the {{ill|lt=medieval period|Q12554|WD=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}}, it was called Kakinomoto-no-miya, and the {{ill|lt=Kamakura period|Q236205|WD=Q236205|1=Kamakura period}} ''{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kakinomoto-no-miya Mandala|1=UNKNOWN}}'' (in the collection of {{ill|lt=Yamato Bunkakan|Q3329639|WD=Q3329639|1=Museum Yamato Bunkakan}}, a national {{ill|lt=Important Cultural Property|Q1188622|WD=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}}) depicts this shrine{{sfn|Great Dictionary of Temples and Shrines|p=832}}. After the {{ill|lt=Nanboku-cho period|Q264012|WD=Q264012|lt=Northern and Southern Courts period|1=Nanboku-chō period}}, it was repeatedly used as a military encampment{{sfn|Great Dictionary of Temples and Shrines|p=832}}.

=== Precincts ===
At the western foot of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Mount Todai-ji|1=UNKNOWN}}, the precinct corresponds to the rear circular section of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Wanishita Shrine Kofun|1=UNKNOWN}}, part of the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Todai-ji-yama Kofun group|1=UNKNOWN}}{{sfn|Great Dictionary of Temples and Shrines|p=832}}.

